member.name: T:Innovator.Client.ElementFactory
member.summary: Class for generating mutable AML objects

remarks.para: An is used to create AML objects (Items, properties, attributes, and more). A factory is needed to create these objects because the objects need to know how to serialize and deserialize base .Net types (e.g. ) according to the time zone and context of a particular server connection. You can get a from a via the property. Alternatively, if you are processing AML without an Aras connection (e.g. reading an AML export file), you can easily get an in from the or the static properties for a factory using either the local or the UTC time zone respectively.
To create an AML structure (that you can easily modify) with an , you can either start with a parameter substituted AML string, or by creating the AML objects directly

When used in the second manner, the API should feel very similar to creating LINQ-to-XML objects. However, using should be preferred as, unlike LINQ, it properly serializes base types and handles time zone conversions

member.name: T:Innovator.Client.ParameterSubstitution
member.summary: Class for substituting @-prefixed parameters with their values

remarks.para: This class will substitute values into an AML template. Using this class to perform the substitution (via creating a ) provides several benefits over other techniques (e.g. )

item.term: String values will be properly escaped for AML.
item.description: For example, Items 1 & 2 are > Item 3 will be encoded as Items 1 & 2 are > Item 3. If you don't want this to happen, add an exclamation mark after your parameter name (e.g. using "<prop>@0</prop>" will encode the string while using "<prop>@0!</prop>" will not perform any encoding

item.term: Basic .Net types will be handled properly
item.description: For example, true will be encoded as 1 and new DateTime(2000, 1, 1) will be encoded as 2000-01-01T00:00:00

remarks.para: Parameters can appear in AML attributes, elements, or in SQL strings. Since AML attributes always are surrounded by quotes, be sure to put your parameter name in quotes as well (whether they are single quotes or double quotes). In SQL, parameters are not quoted as not all values need to be quoted. Rather, the replacement process will decide whether or not quotes are needed. For example,
remarks.code: <Item type='Part' action='@0'> <state condition='in'>(select name from innovator.table where id = @1)</state> </Item>
